06134nam a22006975i 9780822399117DE-B159720210106113355.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210106t19971997ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223991177 a10.1515/97808223991172doi  a(DE-B1597)554121  a(OCoLC)1229161674  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPZ7.1.M246bFas 2018 7aHIS0030002bisacsh04a[E]22300aFormations of Colonial Modernity in East Asia /cTani Barlow. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1997] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (464 p.) :b40 b&w photographs, 2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aa positions book00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: On "Colonial Modernity" -- tThe Fate of "Mr. Science" in China: The Concept of Science and Its Application in Modern Chinese Thought -- tTranslingual Practice: The Discourse of Individualism between China and the West -- tLeaving a Brand on China: Missionary Discourse in the Wake of the Boxer Movement -- tThe Making of Imperial Subjects in Okinawa -- tWriting Out Asia: Modernity, Canon, and Natsume Soseki's Kokoro -- tColonialism and the Sciences of the Tropical Zone: The Academic Analysis of Difference in "the Island Peoples" -- tIn the Scopic Regime of Discovery: Ishikawa Takuboku's Diary in Roman Script and the Gendered Premise of Self-Identity -- tRemembering Pearl Harbor, Forgetting Charlie Chaplin, and the Case of the Disappearing Western Woman: A Picture Story -- tPolitics and the Body Social in Colonial Hong Kong -- tSurveillance and Punishment in Postliberation North Korea -- tThe Discourse of Decolonization and Popular Memory: South Korea -- tColonialism's Career in Postwar China Studies -- tOriental Antiquities/Far Eastern Art -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe essays in Formations of Colonial Modernity in East Asia challenge the idea that notions of modernity and colonialism are mere imports from the West, and show how colonial modernity has evolved from and into unique forms throughout Asia. Although the modernity of non-European colonies is as indisputable as the colonial core of European modernity, until recently East Asian scholarship has tried to view Asian colonialism through the paradigm of colonial India (for instance), failing to recognize anti-imperialist nationalist impulses within differing Asian countries and regions.Demonstrating an impatience with social science models of knowledge, the contributors show that binary categories focused on during the Cold War are no longer central to the project of history writing. By bringing together articles previously published in the journal positions: east asia cultures critique, editor Tani Barlow has demonstrated how scholars construct identity and history, providing cultural critics with new ways to think about these concepts-in the context of Asia and beyond.Chapters address topics such as the making of imperial subjects in Okinawa, politics and the body social in colonial Hong Kong, and the discourse of decolonization and popular memory in South Korea. This is an invaluable collection for students and scholars of Asian studies, postcolonial studies, and anthropology.Contributors. Charles K. Armstrong, Tani E. Barlow, Fred Y. L. Chiu, Chungmoo Choi, Alan S. Christy, Craig Clunas, James A. Fujii, James L. Hevia, Charles Shiro Inouye, Lydia H. Liu, Miriam Silverberg, Tomiyama Ichiro, Wang Hui  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Jan 2021) 0aAnti-imperialist movementszEast AsiaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh1 aChristy, Alan S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarlow, Tani, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aArmstrong, Ch